So if somebody comes to you in anger, you can feel, you can feel the old conditioning, want to bite, you see.

189
00:24:49,182 --> 00:24:58,180
But because you've established this attitude, you very quickly know that all the person wants is for you to listen to them, isn't it?

190
00:24:58,701 --> 00:25:03,191
When you're angry, isn't it all you want to do is for them to listen to what you're saying?

191
00:25:03,211 --> 00:25:09,282
Not only listen in the sense of what you're saying, but what you're feeling, you know, like I am angry with you, you know.

192
00:25:11,170 --> 00:25:15,598
And it's been able just to stay with that in that sort of attending way, you see.

193
00:25:16,079 --> 00:25:20,147
Not in this sort of, I think the word is passive-aggressive, isn't it?

194
00:25:20,789 --> 00:25:22,031
Or aggressive passivity.

195
00:25:23,173 --> 00:25:26,641
It's like you're standing there, you know, and you're not touching me.

196
00:25:26,922 --> 00:25:28,144
Well, I mean, that's really aggressive.

197
00:25:28,786 --> 00:25:30,849
That's going to make them really want to bite.

198
00:25:31,758 --> 00:25:45,078
But if you manifest the fact that you, you know, you feel their anger, you feel, you know, and that there's that empathy with their anger and whatnot, then there's, you know, there's not that aggressive response.

199
00:25:53,571 --> 00:25:58,338
You've always got that magic word, sorry, you see, that drains people's anger, you know.

200
00:25:58,910 --> 00:26:02,154
And then after you've done that, of course, you prove it was their fault anyway.

201
00:26:05,159 --> 00:26:06,421
You win anyway.

202
00:26:06,661 --> 00:26:10,807
Be careful of that.

203
00:26:10,826 --> 00:26:11,709
It's a one-up, you know.

204
00:26:11,808 --> 00:26:17,277
Gotcha.

205
00:26:18,699 --> 00:26:24,066
Now, can you see the link between sitting with your own mental states and sitting with somebody else's?

206
00:26:24,086 --> 00:26:25,769
The inside and the outside.

207
00:26:25,929 --> 00:26:28,613
You're taking the practice directly into your daily life.

208
00:26:33,554 --> 00:26:47,599
When it comes to insight, so all this really is about creating peaceful states around us, how is it that we have this special practice called vipassana, which is about seeing these three characteristics?

209
00:26:48,060 --> 00:26:48,961
How does that work?

210
00:26:49,021 --> 00:26:51,105
How does that translate into your daily life?

211
00:26:51,226 --> 00:26:55,094
Because it's only with those sorts of insights that there are radical changes.

212
00:26:55,153 --> 00:26:56,997
These are root changes.

213
00:26:56,977 --> 00:27:22,613
we can change our personalities we can change our attitudes we can do a lot to change the surface psychology you can even change your body you can do a bit of exercise and stuff like that but it's not getting to the root of it the root problems are to do with these wrong ways of seeing things so where we see permanence there is impermanence

214
00:27:22,593 --> 00:27:32,167
Now you might say, well, I can see impermanence everywhere, but the fact is, when we're struck by crises, then of course we find it a big shock.

215
00:27:32,788 --> 00:27:42,963
It's the level of shock, it's the level of fear which shows us our relationship to a situation which we thought was steady, permanent, unchangeable.

216
00:27:45,019 --> 00:27:47,746
And then there's that business of the wanting and not wanting.

217
00:27:48,086 --> 00:27:53,137
So yeah, that's a bit more obvious, taking that into daily life, and we'll come back to that.

218
00:27:53,518 --> 00:27:57,527
And then there's this other business of anatta, not self, you see.

219
00:27:58,991 --> 00:28:10,977
When you're sitting like this, of course, it's a privileged position because you have found this objective observer place, this observation post, as Jnana Ponica calls it.

220
00:28:10,997 --> 00:28:15,586
He's a pretty famous writer in Theravada, a German.

221
00:28:15,646 --> 00:28:16,950
He's died now.

222
00:28:16,930 --> 00:28:20,056
an observation post, you found this observation post within yourself.

223
00:28:20,076 --> 00:28:26,086
So this is a fairly privileged position you might say, because you're not moving, you're not doing anything, so now you can watch.

224
00:28:26,367 --> 00:28:29,874
You can watch the psychophysical organism in action.

225
00:28:30,355 --> 00:28:34,563
You can see the body feels, the heart emotes, and the mind thinks.

226
00:28:35,263 --> 00:28:36,787
What else is there?

227
00:28:36,807 --> 00:28:37,387
What else is there?

228
00:28:37,407 --> 00:28:38,871
That's it.

229
00:28:39,019 --> 00:29:04,992
and you can see that things are changing, you can see how you're relating to what's inside you and that's something coming from this wrong idea of indulgence and resistance and you can see this business of not me, not mine as you become very clear in your seeing that these are objects

230
00:29:05,615 --> 00:29:07,339
So what's an object can't be the subject.

231
00:29:07,380 --> 00:29:08,082
It's as simple as that.

232
00:29:08,844 --> 00:29:12,292
Even the feeling of self-awareness, as we said, is an object.

233
00:29:12,794 --> 00:29:14,900
You're aware of a self, so you can't be that either.

234
00:29:16,183 --> 00:29:21,919
But it's actually looking at that and constantly re-experiencing that makes these things very obvious to you.

235
00:29:23,671 --> 00:29:29,659
So now how can you have, you know, spiritual insight in daily life?

236
00:29:29,679 --> 00:29:36,288
You know, when you're washing the pots or when you're talking to somebody or when you're doing a job and all that, you see.

237
00:29:37,690 --> 00:29:50,287
Well, the understanding is that this intelligence that is the knowing, this intuitive intelligence, which is prior, prior to the mind with its thoughts, yeah?

238
00:29:50,307 --> 00:29:52,529
It's prior to emotions, right?

239
00:29:52,814 --> 00:29:56,700
Most people think of intuitive intelligence as a feeling.

240
00:29:57,259 --> 00:30:07,595
Sure, it manifests, it sort of communicates its understanding through feeling, but it's not feeling, it's not emotion, and it's not the body either.

241
00:30:08,236 --> 00:30:12,122
And that's what we're discovering every time we access this observation post.

242
00:30:14,498 --> 00:30:40,252
now that intelligence is being primed every time you sit to begin to see life from one of these three perspectives every time you sit, every time you make the conscious effort to see these three characteristics it is being informed, it's informing itself and that manifests in your daily life in various ways

243
00:30:40,891 --> 00:30:59,727
So when this tsunami struck Sri Lanka, there were some very well-meaning counselors went there to help people overcome their trauma, and they were surprised to find that

244
00:30:59,960 --> 00:31:01,663
they'd overcome their trauma.

245
00:31:02,365 --> 00:31:21,781
It wasn't, for them, for people of Eastern mentality, you know, like, it wasn't such a huge trauma that it would be, say, to a Westerner, because they accept, they have the attitude of karma, they have the attitude of impermanence, everything's impermanent, what's the problem, see?

246
00:31:21,761 --> 00:31:29,464
It doesn't mean to say they don't suffer the loss of loved ones and all that, but there isn't this ongoing post-traumatic stress.

247
00:31:30,006 --> 00:31:33,897
See, all that's gone because of that easy acceptance of the way things are.

248
00:31:36,493 --> 00:31:52,798
so now we you see constantly reminding ourselves that there is impermanence everything is impermanent you simply do not know what's going to happen in the next moment you just don't know you know just recently we've had these Israeli attacks on

249
00:31:52,778 --> 00:31:55,862
on Palestine and on the West Bank, you see.

250
00:31:56,143 --> 00:31:57,344
So there were people there.

251
00:31:57,664 --> 00:31:59,027
I mean, they're in dangerous positions.

252
00:31:59,047 --> 00:32:04,555
They know they're dangerous, but some innocent people, you see, their lives have just been blown out.

253
00:32:04,615 --> 00:32:04,974
That's it.

254
00:32:05,496 --> 00:32:06,678
Same with the Israelis.

255
00:32:06,958 --> 00:32:18,094
Not so many, but these bombs come over and like three people have died in a day just from these rockets going over the fence.

256
00:32:18,074 --> 00:32:28,446
And so you're there, you see, you know, frying your chips, and getting your sausages ready, and you've got your HP sauce out, and that's it.

257
00:32:29,708 --> 00:32:34,294
You're up there looking down at all these sausages and all splattered all over the place, and you're floating in mid-air.

258
00:32:34,933 --> 00:32:38,097
See?

259
00:32:38,117 --> 00:32:39,839
I had a case of...

260
00:32:40,121 --> 00:32:43,464
I have a very strange sense of humour, but...

261
00:32:44,566 --> 00:32:45,346
There was a...

262
00:32:46,423 --> 00:32:49,288
Somebody I know is very, she's about 70-odd.

263
00:32:50,289 --> 00:32:55,998
And she met an old-time sweetheart, going way back to her early days.

264
00:32:56,798 --> 00:33:01,445
And, I mean, I got this story, you know, secondhand.

265
00:33:01,465 --> 00:33:03,588
And, well, they fell in love, you know.

266
00:33:04,160 --> 00:33:32,984
and they got married and she brought all her stuff over from America a couple of thousand pounds they set up in this beautiful I went to visit them actually they set up in this lovely little cottage in a nice little country village you know English country village and not so long married I mean you know come of a certain age one has to accept things it seems as though he was just going for the toast out of the toaster when he collapsed

267
00:33:33,573 --> 00:33:42,423
And I've always thought of the horror of dying as you're grabbing hold of a piece of toast.

268
00:33:45,066 --> 00:33:59,422
As you're lifting the piece of toast with marmalade to your mouth, unable to clamp your jaw over it.

269
00:33:59,442 --> 00:34:00,963
To me, it's a nightmare.

270
00:34:03,998 --> 00:34:16,355
So it's a case of, you know, once we grasp the impermanence, you see, it takes away the reverberation of disaster.

271
00:34:17,715 --> 00:34:21,621
It takes away the reverberation of loss, of grief, and that sort of stuff.

272
00:34:22,101 --> 00:34:25,626
There is just the grief, there is just the loss, you know.

273
00:34:26,047 --> 00:34:29,431
There's not behind it some feeling of injustice, you know.

274
00:34:30,458 --> 00:34:34,663
human beings are always clever at making themselves a center of the universe.

275
00:34:34,722 --> 00:34:39,248
It was such a clout to our ego when we realized that the earth actually went round the sun.

276
00:34:39,889 --> 00:34:45,356
And it was even worse when we were told that we were just animals.

277
00:34:47,498 --> 00:34:49,501
We just rose up from the animals.

278
00:34:49,521 --> 00:34:51,563
We were just fitter, that's all.

279
00:34:52,465 --> 00:34:56,469
That was a hit, wasn't it, to the old ego.

280
00:34:58,612 --> 00:35:00,094
So this...

281
00:35:00,260 --> 00:35:10,635
this sense of, what we do as humans, we project our sense of justice onto the universe.

282
00:35:10,655 --> 00:35:13,820
There's no justice in the universe, there's only laws, yeah?

283
00:35:14,481 --> 00:35:20,028
You know, tsunamis happen because earthquakes happen under the sea or something, or a tectonic plate shift.

284
00:35:20,048 --> 00:35:26,318
Nothing to do with justice, nothing to do with morality, to do with the way the earth is, to do with that sort of law, you know?

285
00:35:28,237 --> 00:35:35,474
So when people say, oh, you know, it's a shame he died young and all that, you know, like it was, it's a law.

286
00:35:35,554 --> 00:35:40,644
The body runs along different laws from human justice, and that's the way it is.

287
00:35:44,083 --> 00:35:50,956
So just getting the idea of impermanence, saturating the way we look at things, everything's impermanent, you see.

288
00:35:51,498 --> 00:35:54,402
Even to get up in the morning and say to yourself, everything's impermanent.

289
00:35:54,422 --> 00:35:55,505
I don't know what's going to happen today.

290
00:35:56,085 --> 00:35:57,088
I think I know what's going to happen.

291
00:35:57,367 --> 00:35:58,329
I've got it all planned.

292
00:36:00,148 --> 00:36:28,418
I actually don't know what's gonna happen see so that puts us into this into this mind you see framework you see and the Buddha's great statement about impermanence is that you know when we actually grasp impermanence in its real fullness we realize there's nothing in the world worth holding on to nothing in the world worth holding on to not even ourselves this is the point

293
00:36:30,085 --> 00:36:35,733
Now that, at first, you know, at first it might strike as sort of, you know, a bit frightening and whatnot.

294
00:36:35,753 --> 00:36:37,356
But it's tremendously relaxing, isn't it?

295
00:36:37,577 --> 00:36:38,860
We don't have to hold on to anything anymore.

296
00:36:39,159 --> 00:36:39,521
Yippee!

297
00:36:40,021 --> 00:36:46,271
So it's like when somebody, you know, thieves something from you, you see.

298
00:36:47,179 --> 00:36:49,983
We have this idea that I possess something.

299
00:36:50,324 --> 00:36:55,411
So I possess my mobile.

300
00:36:55,431 --> 00:36:57,112
It's my mobile.

301
00:36:57,132 --> 00:36:58,715
I can prove it in law.

302
00:36:59,356 --> 00:37:01,018
This belongs to me.

303
00:37:01,097 --> 00:37:01,878
I'm attached to it.

304
00:37:02,820 --> 00:37:03,822
And then somebody steals it.

305
00:37:03,922 --> 00:37:05,744
And I'm still going around saying it's my mobile.

306
00:37:08,809 --> 00:37:09,409
It's the thief's.

307
00:37:10,210 --> 00:37:11,431
The thief owns the mobile.

308
00:37:13,387 --> 00:37:15,931
And I'm suffering like mad because they've got my mobile.

309
00:37:16,753 --> 00:37:17,353
I didn't tell them.

310
00:37:21,001 --> 00:37:25,469
And suddenly when you realize actually you can't own anything.

311
00:37:25,630 --> 00:37:27,072
What you can do is use it.

312
00:37:27,454 --> 00:37:28,195
Ah, what a relief.

313
00:37:29,538 --> 00:37:32,884
And then you think, well, you know, the thief might need it more than me.

314
00:37:32,903 --> 00:37:34,025
And you're happy to give it away.

315
00:37:34,427 --> 00:37:35,108
Just like that.

316
00:37:38,344 --> 00:37:42,650
So that impermanence, you see, it seeps into an attitude.

317
00:37:43,210 --> 00:37:46,333
And that's important to understand that.

318
00:37:46,373 --> 00:37:52,320
The Eightfold Path begins with right understanding, and the second one is right attitude.

319
00:37:53,541 --> 00:37:57,487
And if it doesn't drop into an attitude, it just remains at this nice intellectual level.

320
00:37:57,686 --> 00:37:59,548
Oh yeah, everything arises and passes away.

321
00:37:59,588 --> 00:38:00,409
You know, what?

322
00:38:02,952 --> 00:38:06,376
There's no catastrophe when something does arise and pass away, you know.

323
00:38:06,577 --> 00:38:10,260
So it has to sink into, and that's a heart state.

324
00:38:11,300 --> 00:38:14,284
When I say heart state here, I'm not talking really about an emotion.

325
00:38:14,523 --> 00:38:16,085
So an attitude isn't an emotion.

326
00:38:16,766 --> 00:38:18,347
You have to be clear about that.

327
00:38:18,768 --> 00:38:22,791
An attitude is a way of relating as an attitude.

328
00:38:23,032 --> 00:38:23,552
See?

329
00:38:23,572 --> 00:38:25,534
An understanding, everything's impermanent.

330
00:38:25,835 --> 00:38:34,001
Right, now, what does that mean in terms of my relationship to objects, my relationship to people, my relationship to myself, my own body?

331
00:38:33,981 --> 00:38:41,967
see how does that relate and that's your attitude and then of course it manifests in the way we behave in the way we do actually relate moment to moment

332
00:38:48,054 --> 00:38:52,521
Now the next one, you see, which seeps into our daily life is this business of dukkha.

333
00:38:52,621 --> 00:38:55,585
So dukkha, remember, is one of these big words in Buddhism.

334
00:38:55,704 --> 00:39:03,034
It sort of covers everything that makes us unhappy in the widest sense of that meaning.

335
00:39:03,155 --> 00:39:14,028
You know, from the trivialist things, something like that, the most trivial, that's better, from the most trivial thing to, you know, catastrophes.

336
00:39:14,009 --> 00:39:36,405
awful thing, the whole gamut of human misery is contained in this word dukkha which actually means a hard place, that's what it means, this is a hard place and when the Buddha says, you know, go into this, where is the suffering then it's to do with this psychology of wanting and not wanting, wanting and not wanting

337
00:39:38,342 --> 00:39:51,277
Now, just a very sort of change of attitude, you know, just a change of words, like, you know, not getting what you want, but wanting what you get.

338
00:39:52,119 --> 00:39:59,467
So even that, wanting what you get, there's a sort of flip, you know, and you think, oh, and suddenly you're contented.

339
00:40:00,068 --> 00:40:06,375
You know, to be actually, to develop the attitude of contentment with what I've got, you know.

340
00:40:06,675 --> 00:40:19,213
And of course it's difficult in a society which is driven by consumerism, because consumerism depends on your constant discontent.

341
00:40:20,094 --> 00:40:22,237
As soon as you're contented, that's it.

342
00:40:22,318 --> 00:40:25,061
Consumerism collapses the whole industrial base.

343
00:40:26,403 --> 00:40:28,407
I don't want a car, I'm content, I'll walk.

344
00:40:29,248 --> 00:40:31,331
You can't do that.

345
00:40:31,351 --> 00:40:32,311
You can't do that.

346
00:40:32,949 --> 00:40:46,099
you've got to be discontent so this whole feeling of constantly being discontent the whole of the advert is to make you feel discontent that's why you want that you know whatever it is you know

347
00:40:47,632 --> 00:40:58,590
But constantly saying to ourselves, constantly beginning from the platform of, this is okay, this is the way it is, it's fine, it's not a problem, it's good, it's the way it is, content, you see.

348
00:40:59,431 --> 00:41:02,536
And what you do is you begin to separate need from want.

349
00:41:03,117 --> 00:41:06,483
Sometimes you need, you need a new pair of shoes and that's the end of it.

350
00:41:06,851 --> 00:41:08,074
So you go and get a pair of shoes.

351
00:41:08,393 --> 00:41:10,617
And then there's that dividing line.

352
00:41:10,657 --> 00:41:12,960
So you now know this is need, this is want.

353
00:41:13,481 --> 00:41:16,525
Wants come up sometimes for various reasons.

354
00:41:16,666 --> 00:41:21,853
Say to lift your spirit, you might buy yourself something rather pleasant or ask somebody else to do it.

355
00:41:24,757 --> 00:41:32,590
But at least there's not this churning of the heart to go out and constantly exercise this retail therapy.

356
00:41:33,025 --> 00:41:37,871
Seeking comfort in shops, for heaven's sake.

357
00:41:37,891 --> 00:41:38,512
Ridiculous.

358
00:41:41,577 --> 00:41:44,601
I don't feel comfortable unless I'm in Marks and Spencer's.

359
00:41:45,702 --> 00:41:48,025
Ridiculous.

360
00:41:48,045 --> 00:41:49,126
Where do I go when I'm sad?

361
00:41:49,407 --> 00:41:50,228
Marks and Spencer's.

362
00:41:51,610 --> 00:41:56,416
When I feel depressed, I go to Marks and Spencer's.

363
00:41:56,802 --> 00:42:02,588
Like it's been a disaster, Woolworths has gone.

364
00:42:02,610 --> 00:42:05,552
Like it's a catastrophe, Woolworths has gone.

365
00:42:06,514 --> 00:42:09,177
Oh my God.

366
00:42:09,197 --> 00:42:13,402
There's sort of weird sort of ways of relating to the world.

367
00:42:14,103 --> 00:42:19,992
So you can see that even now, we're watching the suffering of wanting, not wanting.

368
00:42:21,574 --> 00:42:33,974
You know, a desire comes up, we want to think about this, we want to plan our holiday, you know, and we're constantly pulling ourselves off and feeling that strong desire, that willfulness in us, you see.

369
00:42:33,994 --> 00:42:42,668
When it's something unpleasant, you see, that's even more, that's sort of more difficult, but to be able to be easy with unpleasantness, see.

370
00:42:42,929 --> 00:42:47,396
Now it's cold, the difference between a room temperature and outside is vicious.

371
00:42:48,052 --> 00:42:52,438
And, you know, our attitude is to sort of resist the cold.

372
00:42:52,458 --> 00:42:57,766
We sort of, you know, rush from the bungalow to here to get out of the cold.

373
00:42:58,407 --> 00:43:01,152
Instead of sort of greeting it, ah, cold, great.

374
00:43:02,894 --> 00:43:06,721
Just, ah, you know, the freshness of it, you know.

375
00:43:06,740 --> 00:43:08,523
I'm not suggesting you catch a cold, you understand.

376
00:43:11,507 --> 00:43:14,333
And to take that attitude into daily life.

377
00:43:14,793 --> 00:43:15,213
You can do it.

378
00:43:15,373 --> 00:43:15,775
You can do it.

379
00:43:16,195 --> 00:43:20,001
And again, it's sort of reminding ourselves, this constant self-reminder.

380
00:43:20,021 --> 00:43:24,228
So as soon as we see ourselves passing a shop and wanting that, yeah, hold on.

381
00:43:25,329 --> 00:43:26,331
Just pull it back.

382
00:43:26,733 --> 00:43:30,157
Pull back that sort of energy.

383
00:43:30,137 --> 00:43:37,853
And of course, it can be, and all that energy, by the way, that we're using in getting what we want, it's not being wasted.

384
00:43:37,873 --> 00:43:39,054
You can displace it.

385
00:43:39,135 --> 00:43:41,478
You can take your interest elsewhere.

386
00:43:41,518 --> 00:43:48,231
You know, in the old days, they used to talk about sublimation, sort of a religious idea of sublimating your desires, you know.

387
00:43:48,753 --> 00:43:50,896
You don't hear that word often these days, you know.

388
00:43:51,282 --> 00:44:05,210
And that's because, really, I suppose, through the agencies of people like Freud, people think that there are certain instincts and desires that are blocked or locked into certain things, like our sexual appetite.

389
00:44:05,431 --> 00:44:08,177
They're just stuck there and you can't get rid of them, you know.

390
00:44:08,157 --> 00:44:35,818
but in spiritual terms sublimation means that you guide that energy and put it somewhere else it's all it is the mind and body as we know from our great quantum physics is that it's just energy so if you decide to displace the energy you see away from say eroticism and you put it into art then that's your sublimation you know

391
00:44:36,592 --> 00:44:39,820
That's what you mean by sublimating.

392
00:44:39,840 --> 00:44:52,068
And that transference, that transformation of energy away from desires which you see are unwholesome, right, to desires which you see are wholesome, is part and parcel of that process, right?

393
00:44:53,197 --> 00:45:10,541
I'm not suggesting that erotic desires are per se unwholesome, and they obviously have their place in time, but if you find them sort of cringing on the mind, sort of obsessive, then it's a case of slowly displacing them, putting our interests elsewhere.

394
00:45:14,206 --> 00:45:15,588
So it's the same with shopping, you see.

395
00:45:17,130 --> 00:45:21,836
People put a lot of interest in shopping, in fashion and all that sort of stuff.

396
00:45:22,119 --> 00:45:28,606
All they have to do is just to draw their interest elsewhere, just to re-educate themselves.

397
00:45:28,626 --> 00:45:29,186
That's all it is.

398
00:45:29,206 --> 00:45:31,228
It's just a process of re-education.

399
00:45:31,708 --> 00:45:33,670
But they won't do it unless they see the suffering.

400
00:45:33,791 --> 00:45:34,371
That's the point.

401
00:45:34,972 --> 00:45:42,079
And the problem with pleasure, the problem with joy, indulgent joy, is that while you're in it, it's great.

402
00:45:42,480 --> 00:45:43,119
That's the problem.

403
00:45:43,601 --> 00:45:47,925
And you're prepared often to suffer the consequences so you can have this bit of joy.

404
00:45:53,221 --> 00:45:55,063
It's only when you get the comeback, you know.

405
00:45:55,623 --> 00:46:02,452
I was just thinking there of a friend who, a friend's father, you see, always smoked, always smoked, you see.

406
00:46:02,733 --> 00:46:05,936
Then he had a heart attack, and he suddenly stopped, just like that.

407
00:46:07,119 --> 00:46:08,119
He got the comeback.

408
00:46:08,521 --> 00:46:12,925
It's unfortunate that it was so strong a comeback, but it just shows, you know.

409
00:46:12,945 --> 00:46:19,735
Now, the comeback of all indulgence is, you know, the craving, right?

410
00:46:21,014 --> 00:46:23,936
The possibility of grief, if you lose what it is, you treasure.

411
00:46:25,119 --> 00:46:28,402
The anxiety that once you've got something, the anxiety of losing it.

412
00:46:28,503 --> 00:46:30,965
That's why we've got a massive insurance industry.

413
00:46:33,407 --> 00:46:35,530
And of course the frustration, not getting it when you want.

414
00:46:36,672 --> 00:46:37,313
Getting what you want.

415
00:46:38,074 --> 00:46:48,726
So by taking this inner understanding of wanting, not wanting, into daily life, you see, it moves you towards contentment.

416
00:46:49,634 --> 00:46:52,182
That's the joy, that's the subtle joy.

417
00:46:52,423 --> 00:47:01,197
And that's another reason why to develop this calmness on the breath and to begin to see there's actually a very delicious place to be.

418
00:47:01,311 --> 00:47:08,021
Often we find it, but we do it in contrast to agitation, in contrast to stress.

419
00:47:08,543 --> 00:47:15,873
We'll go home and just flop in the chair and just for a moment there's no radio, there's no nothing, we just sort of sink into the quietness of the moment.

420
00:47:16,574 --> 00:47:26,070
We might walk into a park or come out into the country or sit in the garden and just for a moment we'll actually sink into that space, to that little bit of peace, you see.

421
00:47:26,438 --> 00:47:30,282
but we'll do it as a sort of antidote to another thing.

422
00:47:30,543 --> 00:47:42,360
Whereas what we want to do is to develop it as a prime condition, something that we can return to at any time, and as it were, remains a substrate beneath our psychology.

423
00:47:42,981 --> 00:47:48,829
There's always this deep sense of calmness within us, no matter what we're doing on the surface.

424
00:47:50,072 --> 00:47:53,255
And again, it's just training, it's just training ourselves to do that.

425
00:47:54,467 --> 00:48:04,282
So the breath there is watching the breath, feeling the breath, seeing it as a place where we can develop this calmness and peace is directly related into daily life.

426
00:48:05,326 --> 00:48:06,891
Because you can always come back to your breath.

427
00:48:08,693 --> 00:48:21,739
You know, when I say stop every so often, you know, just come to an end of what you're doing, you see, and catch what it is you've accumulated, some anxiety, some stress, whatever, and allow it to pass, there's always the breath, you see.

428
00:48:21,759 --> 00:48:26,889
And the breath will be a place that you'll go to, just like your garden or the park.

429
00:48:26,909 --> 00:48:30,617
It's a place where you just find that inner peace for a moment.

430
00:48:35,844 --> 00:48:51,186
Now the sense of not-self is one of the key factors and it's in his second talk, the second talk he gives to his five disciples, at the end of which they're all fully liberated by the way.

431
00:48:51,206 --> 00:48:59,878
He says clearly, he says, that which arises and passes away cannot be under your control.

432
00:49:00,010 --> 00:49:13,786
Now, every time you get into the self, one of the ways that the self manifests is the desire to control power.

433
00:49:15,369 --> 00:49:22,137
Every time you see yourself wanting to control a situation, control a person, you'll know it's coming from the self.

434
00:49:23,045 --> 00:49:29,731
It's not the same as being in charge or being an authority in which you are given the power to make decisions.

435
00:49:30,413 --> 00:49:38,380
I mean that's an occasion where you take on responsibility and you try to make the wisest decisions you can.

436
00:49:39,262 --> 00:49:52,275
But in terms of this other business, where things are not going your way and you're getting angry, where you're getting angry with your spouse, your partner because they're not doing what you want them to do, or your kids.

437
00:49:53,385 --> 00:50:00,003
and you're getting frustrated and anxious and all that and that's all to do with this sense of wanting to control you see

438
00:50:04,978 --> 00:50:25,148
So again, it's this business of taking that into daily life and just recognizing that our control over things is pretty limited and that things happen outside of our control and that there's, in the old phrase, you gotta go with the flow, you gotta be in harmony with what's happening

439
00:50:25,128 --> 00:50:30,755
That harmony is not always pleasant, but you're actually moving with it.

440
00:50:30,936 --> 00:50:34,862
You're not trying to control something which is actually outside your control.

441
00:50:35,742 --> 00:50:40,789
And I think this comes most obvious when we get involved in politics.

442
00:50:42,813 --> 00:50:44,396
Politics in the wider sense of the meaning.

443
00:50:44,436 --> 00:50:48,942
People's issues, like the business going on with climate change and so on.

444
00:50:49,427 --> 00:51:06,947
the economy and all that sort of stuff which are not to be confused with sort of small party politics one can see what has to be done everyone can see what has to be done but there's not the political will

445
00:51:06,978 --> 00:51:08,298
You can see it, you see.

446
00:51:08,539 --> 00:51:11,402
So there arises in people a certain frustration, you see.

447
00:51:11,943 --> 00:51:15,847
And that's really not accepting these two rings that are around us.

448
00:51:15,907 --> 00:51:17,329
The first one being one of power.

449
00:51:18,170 --> 00:51:20,552
What you can do to help the situation.

450
00:51:21,432 --> 00:51:23,675
And if you step beyond that, you're into frustration.

451
00:51:23,735 --> 00:51:25,016
You're into despair.

452
00:51:25,056 --> 00:51:28,181
And that takes an act of humility.

453
00:51:28,860 --> 00:51:31,925
Humility, it doesn't mean, you know, humble, humble.

454
00:51:32,284 --> 00:51:34,246
It just means seeing yourself as you really are.

455
00:51:34,387 --> 00:51:36,849
That's what humility originally meant.

456
00:51:37,672 --> 00:51:42,181
And the other ring is influence, whereby you can get other people to do what you think is right.

457
00:51:43,023 --> 00:51:44,184
Beyond that, there's nothing you can do.

458
00:51:45,586 --> 00:51:52,780
Nothing you can do in any physical sense, but we do have another outlet which allows us to feel at least that we are

459
00:51:54,277 --> 00:51:56,704
shall we say, in communion.

460
00:51:57,847 --> 00:52:00,072
And that is, of course, to offer metta.

461
00:52:00,092 --> 00:52:11,679
I mean, that's the joy of metta, that you can do nothing, but at least you can send out thoughts of intentions, goodwill intentions towards a situation.

462
00:52:14,916 --> 00:52:27,541
even if we don't believe that they actually affect people, at least it's a way in which we might feel within ourselves that we're doing what we can, full stop, develop a goodwill.

463
00:52:30,306 --> 00:52:37,438
Now such is the quality of this intuitive intelligence, you see, is that it can have insights at any time.

464
00:52:37,978 --> 00:52:44,889
And it's well known in the Mahasi tradition that insights don't normally come when you're sitting.

465
00:52:45,570 --> 00:52:47,994
It's when you get up and do something that the insights come.

466
00:52:49,038 --> 00:52:55,771
And the reason is that often when we're sitting, we're very subtly trying to achieve something, trying to see something.

467
00:52:55,791 --> 00:53:00,219
And then when we get up from the posture, we sort of say, all right, nothing happened there, forget it, and off we go.

468
00:53:02,123 --> 00:53:07,653
But we retain that mindfulness, and lo and behold, there are these sudden insights that come.

469
00:53:08,512 --> 00:53:15,891
Because this intelligence has been released from this craving, been released from the self just for that moment.

470
00:53:15,911 --> 00:53:22,690
So it's not as though insights can't come at any time of the day, any time you're awake, once this mindfulness is established.

471
00:53:25,235 --> 00:53:33,344
In fact, the Mahāsī's teacher, that's the Mahāsī, in case you didn't know, when he was about 50, I suppose.

472
00:53:34,125 --> 00:53:46,577
The Mahāsī's teacher is said to have intuited in anicca, the impermanence, as a direct experience of momentary arising and passing away as a dog passed by.

473
00:53:47,219 --> 00:53:49,521
There wasn't a dog, there was just a dogging.

474
00:53:49,889 --> 00:53:53,494
The dog arose and passed away momentarily.

475
00:53:53,514 --> 00:53:55,177
Because that's the teaching of Anitta.

476
00:53:55,257 --> 00:54:03,309
It isn't something which is changing in the sense that you might take a piece of clay and you make a cup and then you screw it up and you make a saucer.

477
00:54:03,329 --> 00:54:04,210
So it's the same clay.

478
00:54:05,552 --> 00:54:06,994
And the Buddha's teaching is quite radical.

479
00:54:07,235 --> 00:54:09,938
It actually collapses into potential or nothing.

480
00:54:09,958 --> 00:54:11,119
I can't say nothing.

481
00:54:11,201 --> 00:54:12,643
It collapses into a potential.

482
00:54:12,663 --> 00:54:13,603
It's not there.

483
00:54:14,065 --> 00:54:16,228
And out of there, it arises again.

484
00:54:16,789 --> 00:54:16,909
Right?

485
00:54:18,998 --> 00:54:48,532
that's what's happening the universe is stroboscopic it's not continuous in the Buddhist teaching so for him that was a deep enough insight for what we call one of the paths and fruits stream entrance or whatever level he was at so that's I hope I've sort of made fairly clear the intimate connection between your meditation and daily life yes

486
00:54:50,217 --> 00:54:52,722
If I happen you, you can leave little notes of complaint.

487
00:54:58,333 --> 00:54:58,773
Kindly.

488
00:54:59,815 --> 00:55:03,382
Notes of complaint.

489
00:55:13,824 --> 00:55:18,353
And remember that the root thing is this constant establishment of mindfulness.

490
00:55:18,592 --> 00:55:27,568
And just as a last word, in the discourse on loving-kindness, can you pass me your book there, please?

491
00:55:27,588 --> 00:55:29,211
Which we chant in the morning, you see.

492
00:55:29,351 --> 00:55:32,498
The Buddha's urging us to develop this loving-kindness.

493
00:55:34,059 --> 00:55:38,527
And at the end, you see, where is he sitting?

494
00:55:38,547 --> 00:55:38,989
Just a minute.

495
00:55:43,170 --> 00:55:48,387
So he says, whether you are standing, walking, sitting or lying down.

496
00:55:48,708 --> 00:55:52,338
So those are the same instructions for mindfulness.

497
00:55:52,358 --> 00:55:53,221
Sitting, walking, lying.

498
00:55:53,242 --> 00:55:55,728
In other words, in any posture, doing anything.

499
00:55:56,114 --> 00:56:01,746
So long as you're awake, so long as you are mindful, you should develop this mindfulness.

500
00:56:01,806 --> 00:56:07,579
And here, he's talking about a mindfulness saturated with loving kindness.

501
00:56:07,820 --> 00:56:09,143
Saturated with goodwill.

502
00:56:09,625 --> 00:56:10,967
That's a bit better.

503
00:56:11,168 --> 00:56:11,548
Goodwill.

504
00:56:11,608 --> 00:56:13,313
Because it's not meant to be an emotional thing, is it?

505
00:56:14,103 --> 00:56:26,561
This, they say, is the noblest way to live, and if you do not fall into bad ways, but live well and develop insight, and are no longer attached to all the desires of the senses, then truly you will never need to be reborn to this world again.

506
00:56:27,442 --> 00:56:28,163
So there you have it.

507
00:56:29,385 --> 00:56:31,588
Mindfulness saturated with good wishes.

508
00:56:32,614 --> 00:56:39,108
And in the morning when I, you know, after chanting, I say, you know, make your resolution for the day, you see.

509
00:56:39,148 --> 00:56:44,340
That's an important moment, you see, because that's going to set the underground tone of the day.

510
00:56:45,021 --> 00:56:49,070
So find a little phrase for yourself, you know, to live...

511
00:56:49,050 --> 00:56:54,219
To live consciously with goodwill or something like that which strikes you as the way you want to be.

512
00:56:54,259 --> 00:57:02,090
It's also good to also create something that you're not going to do.

513
00:57:02,650 --> 00:57:04,673
You're not going to go down that road today.

514
00:57:05,175 --> 00:57:06,336
Keep it in today, you see.

515
00:57:06,416 --> 00:57:07,297
Don't go beyond today.

516
00:57:07,318 --> 00:57:07,998
It gets depressing.

517
00:57:09,481 --> 00:57:11,824
Because I think I'm going to be like this for the rest of my life.

518
00:57:11,844 --> 00:57:12,425
Yeah.

519
00:57:13,300 --> 00:57:16,485
If you do it day by day, it's manageable, isn't it?

520
00:57:16,666 --> 00:57:17,166
Just today.

521
00:57:17,427 --> 00:57:18,208
Today I'll be good.

522
00:57:18,309 --> 00:57:20,492
Tomorrow I'll play hell.

523
00:57:20,552 --> 00:57:25,661
But today, if we keep doing that, we should arrive.

524
00:57:25,681 --> 00:57:30,030
So I can only hope my words have been of some assistance.

525
00:57:30,771 --> 00:57:37,603
May you be liberated from all suffering sooner rather than later.

